Trim the @pak choi{1} then halve lengthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @carrot{1} then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways into small pieces.

Halve the @lime{1}.

Thinly slice the @chilli{1}.

Place a large #pot{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the @prawns{180%grams} and carrot.

Fry until prawns are cooked and carrot is softened, ~{4-6%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{2%sachets} and @korma curry paste{1%sachet} and cook for ~{2-3%mins}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{1%pack}, @vegetable stock{1%sachet} and 300ml @water{to taste} (double for 4p).

Bring to the boil, cover and simmer for ~{8-10%mins}.

While the laksa simmers, place a #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, lay in the pak choi. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Cook on one side for ~{2%mins} then turn over and cook for another ~{2%mins}.

Add the garlic to the pak choi and fry for ~{1%min}. It should be slightly browned and charred.

Add a splash of @water{to taste}, pop a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) on the pan and leave to steam for another ~{3%mins}.

When the laksa has 1 min of cooking time remaining, add the @udon noodles{300%grams}.

Stir carefully to separate the noodles and allow them to warm through.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a squeeze of lime juice.

Divide the prawn laksa between #bowls{}.

Top with garlic pak choi and sliced chilli (use less if you don't like spice).

Cut any remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside.

> A laksa is a saucy, spicy noodle dish that hails from Southeast Asia. Common components include noodles, aromatic elements, and toppings such as chicken, prawn or fish.